              How Many Calories Are in Sandwiches?
              Sandwiches are a convenient and satisfying meal option, but do you know how many calories they contain? In this video, we'll look at some common types of sandwiches and their nutrition facts.

              Popular sandwich ingredients

                Bread is the basic component of most sandwiches, and serves as a container or wrapper for the fillings
              • Bread
                • Cheese is a versatile and flavorful ingredient that can be sliced, grated, melted, or spread on sandwiches
              • Cheese
                • Ham is a type of cured pork that is often sliced and used as a sandwich filling, especially in combination with cheese
              • Ham
                • Lettuce is a leafy vegetable that adds crunch and freshness to sandwiches, and can also act as a barrier between bread and moist fillings
              • Lettuce
                • Tomato is a juicy and colorful fruit that enhances the flavor and nutrition of sandwiches, and pairs well with cheese, ham, and other ingredients
              • Tomato

              Health benefits and risks of sandwiches

                Vegetables are a good source of dietary fiber, vitamins, minerals, and antioxidants that can help prevent or reduce the risk of chronic diseases such as diabetes, heart disease, and some cancers. They also add flavor, color, and texture to sandwiches.
              • Vegetables
                • Cheese is a rich source of protein, calcium, phosphorus, and other nutrients that are essential for bone health and muscle function. Cheese also contains probiotics that can improve gut health and immunity. However, cheese can also be high in fat, sodium, and calories, which can increase the risk of obesity, hypertension, and cardiovascular disease if consumed in excess.
              • Cheese
                • Meat is a high-quality source of protein, iron, zinc, and other micronutrients that are important for growth, development, and immune function. Meat can also enhance the flavor and satiety of sandwiches. However, meat can also contain harmful bacteria, hormones, antibiotics, and environmental contaminants that can cause infections, allergies, and cancers if not properly cooked or stored. Meat can also be high in saturated fat and cholesterol, which can increase the risk of heart disease and stroke if consumed in large amounts.
              • Meat
                • Bread is a staple food that provides carbohydrates, energy, and dietary fiber. Bread can also be fortified with vitamins and minerals such as folic acid, iron, and iodine. Bread can also be made from different grains, seeds, and flours that can offer variety and diversity to sandwiches. However, bread can also be high in refined carbohydrates, gluten, and additives that can cause blood sugar spikes, inflammation, and digestive issues in some people. Bread can also contribute to weight gain and dental decay if consumed in excess.
              • Bread
